 and the political affect contemporary social worlds. The contributors to Anthropos and the Material examine these challenges by questioning and complicating long-held understandings of the divide between humans and things. They present ethnographic case studies from across the globe, addressing myriad topics that range from labor, economics, and colonialism to technology, culture, the environment, agency, and diversity. In foregrounding the importance of connecting natural and social histories, the instability and intangibility of the material, and the ways in which the lively encounters between the human and the nonhuman challenge conceptions of liberal humanism, the contributors point to new understandings of the capacities of people and things to act, transform, and adapt to a changing world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAnthropologyxEnvironmental aspects. 0aEnvironmentalismxPolitical aspects. 0aEnvironmentalismxSocial aspects. 0aEthnologyxPolitical aspects. 0aGeology, StratigraphicyAnthropocene. 0aHuman ecologyxPolitical aspects. 0aNaturexEffect of human beings onxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aHarvey, Penny, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKrohn-Hansen, Christian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNustad, Knut G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478003311zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478003311423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478003311.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles